  publisher = {arXiv},
  urldate = {2023-12-14},
  abstract = {Young, low-mass Brown Dwarfs orbiting early-type stars, with low mass ratios (\$q{\textbackslash}lesssim0.01\$), appear intrinsically rare and present a formation dilemma: could a handful of these objects be the highest mass outcomes of ``planetary" formation channels (bottom up within a protoplanetary disk), or are they more representative of the lowest mass ``failed binaries" (formed via disk fragmentation, or core fragmentation)? Additionally, their orbits can yield model-independent dynamical masses, and when paired with wide wavelength coverage and accurate system age estimates, can constrain evolutionary models in a regime where the models have a wide dispersion depending on initial conditions. We present new interferometric observations of the \$16{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}mathrm\{Myr\}\$ substellar companion HD{\textasciitilde}136164{\textasciitilde}Ab (HIP{\textasciitilde}75056{\textasciitilde}Ab) with VLTI/GRAVITY and an updated orbit fit including proper motion measurements from the Hipparcos-Gaia Catalogue of Accelerations. We estimate a dynamical mass of \$35{\textbackslash}pm10{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}mathrm\{M\_J\}\$ (\$q{\textbackslash}sim0.02\$), making HD{\textasciitilde}136164{\textasciitilde}Ab the youngest substellar companion with a dynamical mass estimate. The new mass and newly constrained orbital eccentricity (\$e=0.44{\textbackslash}pm0.03\$) and separation (\$22.5{\textbackslash}pm1{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}mathrm\{au\}\$) could indicate that the companion formed via the low-mass tail of the Initial Mass Function. Our atmospheric fit to the {\textbackslash}texttt\{SPHINX\} M-dwarf model grid suggests a sub-solar C/O ratio of \$0.45\$, and \$3{\textbackslash}times\$ solar metallicity, which could indicate formation in the circumstellar disk via disk fragmentation. Either way, the revised mass estimate likely excludes ``bottom-up" formation via core accretion in the circumstellar disk. HD{\textasciitilde}136164{\textasciitilde}Ab joins a select group of young substellar objects with dynamical mass estimates; epoch astrometry from future {\textbackslash}textit\{Gaia\} data releases will constrain the dynamical mass of this crucial object further.},
