  abstract = {\emph{Context{$<$}i/{$>$}. Young brown dwarfs exhibit atmospheric characteristics similar to those of super-Jupiters, providing a unique opportunity to study planetary atmospheres. Atmospheric retrievals of high-resolution spectra reveal detailed properties of these objects, with elemental and isotopic ratios offering insights into their formation history. The ESO SupJup Survey, utilising CRIRES\textsuperscript{+{$<$}sup/{$>$} on the Very Large Telescope, aims to assess the role of \textsuperscript{12{$<$}sup/{$>$}C/\textsuperscript{13{$<$}sup/{$>$}C as a formation tracer.\emph{Aims{$<$}i/{$>$}. We present observations of three young brown dwarfs: 2MASS J12003792-7845082, TWA 28, and 2MASS J08561384-1342242. Our goal is to constrain their chemical compositions, thermal profiles, surface gravities, spin rotations, and \textsuperscript{12{$<$}sup/{$>$}C/\textsuperscript{13{$<$}sup/{$>$}C.\emph{Methods{$<$}i/{$>$}. We conducted atmospheric retrievals of CRIRES\textsuperscript{+{$<$}sup/{$>$} \emph{K{$<$}i/{$>$}-band spectra, coupling the radiative transfer code petitRADTRANS with the Bayesian inference algorithm MultiNest.\emph{Results{$<$}i/{$>$}. The retrievals provide a detailed characterisation of the atmospheres of the three objects. We report the volume mixing ratios of the main molecular and atomic species: H\textsubscript{2{$<$}sub/{$>$}\textsuperscript{16{$<$}sup/{$>$}O,\textsuperscript{12{$<$}sup/{$>$}CO, HF, Na, Ca, and Ti, including the novel detection of hydrogen fluoride (HF) in the atmosphere of a brown dwarf. We determine \textsuperscript{12{$<$}sup/{$>$}C/\textsuperscript{13{$<$}sup/{$>$}C values of 81\textsubscript{-19{$<$}sub/{$>$}\textsuperscript{+28{$<$}sup/{$>$} and 79\textsubscript{-14{$<$}sub/{$>$}\textsuperscript{+20{$<$}sup/{$>$} in the atmospheres of TWA 28 and J0856, respectively, with strong significance ({$>$}3\emph{{$\sigma<$}i/{$>$}). We also report tentative evidence ({\textasciitilde}2\emph{{$\sigma<$}i/{$>$}) of \textsup