  urldate = {2021-05-18},
  abstract = {K2 observations of the weak-lined T Tauri binary V928 Tau A+B show the detection of a single, asymmetric eclipse which may be due to a previously unknown substellar companion eclipsing one component of the binary with an orbital period \${$>\$$} 66 days. Over an interval of about 9 hours, one component of the binary dims by around 60\%, returning to its normal brightness about 5 hours later. From modeling of the eclipse shape we find evidence that the eclipsing companion may be surrounded by a disk or a vast ring system. The modeled disk has a radius of \$0.9923{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}pm{\textbackslash},0.0005{\textbackslash},R\_*\$, with an inclination of \$56.78{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}pm{\textbackslash}, 0.03{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}circ\$, a tilt of \$41.22{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}pm{\textbackslash},0.05{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}circ\$, an impact parameter of \$-0.2506{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}pm{\textbackslash},0.0002{\textbackslash},R\_*\$ and an opacity of 1.00. The occulting disk must also move at a transverse velocity of \$6.637{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}pm{\textbackslash},0.002{\textbackslash},R\_*{\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}mathrm\{day\}{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$, which depending on whether it orbits V928 Tau A or B, corresponds to approximately 73.53 or 69.26 \${\textbackslash}mathrm\{km s\}{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$. A search in ground based archival data reveals additional dimming events, some of which suggest periodicity, but no unambiguous period associated with the eclipse observed by K2. We present a new epoch of astrometry which is used to further refine the orbit of the binary, presenting a new lower bound of 67 years, and constraints on the possible orbital periods of the eclipsing companion. The binary is also separated by 18" (\${\textbackslash}sim\$2250 au) from the lower mass CFHT-BD-Tau 7, which is likely associated with V928 Tau A+B. We also present new high dispersion optical spectroscopy that we use to characterize the unresolved stellar binary.},
