  publisher = {arXiv},
  urldate = {2024-03-04},
  abstract = {Recent measurements of carbon isotope ratios in both protoplanetary disks and exoplanet atmospheres have suggested a possible transfer of significant carbon isotope fractionation from disks to planets. For a clearer understanding of the isotopic link between disks and planets, it is important to measure the carbon isotope ratios in various species. In this paper, we present a detection of the \${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN \$N=2-1\$ hyperfine lines in the TW Hya disk with the Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array. This is the first spatially-resolved detection of \${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN in disks, which enables us to measure the spatially resolved \${\textasciicircum}\{12\}\$CN/\${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN ratio for the first time. We conducted non-local thermal equilibrium modeling of the \${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN lines in conjunction with previously observed \${\textasciicircum}\{12\}\$CN lines to derive the kinetic temperature, \$\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_2\}\$ volume density, and column densities of \${\textasciicircum}\{12\}\$CN and \${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN. The \$\{{\textbackslash}rm H\_2\}\$ volume density is found to range between \$ (4 - 10){\textbackslash}times10{\textasciicircum}7 {\textbackslash} \{{\textbackslash}rm cm{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}\}\$, suggesting that CN molecules mainly reside in the disk upper layer. The \${\textasciicircum}\{12\}\$CN/\${\textasciicircum}\{13\}\$CN ratio is measured to be \$ 70{\textasciicircum}\{+9\}\_\{-6\}\$ at \$30 {$<$} r {$<$} 80\$ au from the central star, which is similar to the \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{12\}C/{\textasciicircum}\{13\}C\$ ratio in the interstellar medium. However, this value differs from the previously reported values found for other carbon-bearing molecules (CO and HCN) in the TW Hya disk. This could be self-consistently explained by different emission layer heights for different molecules combined with preferential sequestration of \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{12\}C\$ into the solid phase towards the disk midplane. This study reveals the complexity of the carbon isotope fractionation operating in disks.},
