  abstract = {Located 10.888 pc from Earth, COCONUTS-2b is a planetary-mass companion to a young (150--800 Myr) M3 star, with a wide orbital separation (6471 au) and a low companion-to-host mass ratio (\$0.021{\textbackslash}pm0.005\$). We have studied the atmospheric properties of COCONUTS-2b using newly acquired 1.0--2.5{\textasciitilde}\${\textbackslash}mu\$m spectroscopy from Gemini/Flamingos-2. The spectral type of COCONUTS-2b is refined to T\$9.5 {\textbackslash}pm 0.5\$ based on comparisons with T/Y dwarf spectral templates. We have conducted an extensive forward-modeling analysis, comparing the near-infrared spectrum and mid-infrared broadband photometry with sixteen state-of-the-art atmospheric model grids developed for brown dwarfs and self-luminous exoplanets near the T/Y transition. The {\textbackslash}texttt\{PH\$\_\{3\}\$-free ATMO2020++\}, {\textbackslash}texttt\{ATMO2020++\}, and {\textbackslash}texttt\{Exo-REM\} models best match the specific observations of COCONUTS-2b, regardless of variations in the input spectrophotometry. This analysis suggests the presence of disequilibrium chemistry, along with a diabatic thermal structure and/or clouds, in the atmosphere of COCONUTS-2b. All models predict fainter \$Y\$-band fluxes than observed, highlighting uncertainties in the alkali chemistry models and opacities. We determine a bolometric luminosity of \${\textbackslash}log\{(L\_\{{\textbackslash}rm bol\}/L\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\})\}=-6.18\$ dex, with a 0.5 dex-wide range of \$[-6.43,-5.93]\$ dex that accounts for various assumptions of models. Using thermal evolution models, we derive an effective temperature of \$T\_\{{\textbackslash}rm eff\}=483{\textasciicircum}\{+44\}\_\{-53\}\$ K, a surface gravity of \${\textbackslash}log\{(g)\}=4.19{\textasciicircum}\{+0.18\}\_\{-0.13\}\$ dex, a radius of \$R=1.11{\textasciicircum}\{+0.03\}\_\{-0.04\}\$ R\$\_\{{\textbackslash}rm Jup\}\$, and a mass of \$M=8 {\textbackslash}pm 2\$ M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}rm Jup\}